   Application-NT-Annual, Sarajevo, BOSNIA \& HERCEG, JUN 26-28, 2025},
Organization = {Bosnian-Herzegovinian American Academy of Arts and Sciences},
Abstract = {In recent years, the integration of artificial Intelligence (AI) in
   education has gained global attention, with a focus on enhancing STEM
   education and addressing the underrepresentation of females in these
   fields. AI, which encompasses machine learning, speech recognition, and
   natural language processing, is reshaping industries and societies, and
   its impact is extending into education. Schools and institutions have
   recognized the need for AI education, incorporating concepts like
   perception, learning, and social influence into curricula. However, the
   implementation of AI requires thoughtful consideration of
   age-appropriate tools and the balance between simplifying AI concepts
   for students while solving real-world problems. In STEM education, AI
   applications can assist in creating personalized learning environments,
   enabling teachers to assess student performance and behavior. AI
   chatbots, available 24/7, are becoming a valuable resource for
   programming education, offering personalized assistance. Despite their
   advantages, concerns about privacy, reduced human interaction, and the
   decline of critical thinking persist. In countries like South Korea,
   China, and Japan, national curricula have integrated AI education, with
   South Korea advancing AI programs from primary to secondary schools.
   However, challenges remain, including teacher competence in AI-related
   subjects like machine learning and AI ethics. The article discusses the
   role of AI in student assessment, particularly in the UK, where AI-based
   algorithms were used to predict student performance during the pandemic.
   It highlights the benefits and risks of AI in education, emphasizing the
   need for AI literacy and ethical guidelines to ensure responsible AI use
   in schools worldwide.},
