Note = {27th International Conference on Interactive Collaborative Learning-ICL,
   Tallinn, ESTONIA, SEP 24-27, 2024},
Abstract = {The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence (AI) technologies is
   driving significant changes across both industry and academia, fostering
   increased autonomy in various processes. This influence extends to all
   key stakeholders in the education sector, including students, teachers,
   and institutions. Previous research suggests that students often use AI
   tools inappropriately and without adequate knowledge. Addressing this
   issue, our study investigates the usage patterns of AI tools for
   homework tasks among programming students at TalTech IT College in
   Estonia, a leading European country in educational innovation. Our
   findings reveal a substantial dependence on AI tools, with 74\% of
   students utilizing them for homework. The most frequently used tools are
   OpenAI's ChatGPT-3 and ChatGPT-4, followed by Microsoft Copilot. The
   results underscore the positive aspects of AI tool usage from the
   students' perspective, highlighting the potential benefits these
   technologies offer in enhancing learning experiences. However, it also
   points to a significant issue: many students do not cite the use of AI
   tools in their homework, indicating a need for greater transparency and
   understanding of ethical AI use. These findings suggest the necessity of
   integrating regular AI courses at all levels of study to ensure students
   are well-informed and can use AI responsibly and effectively.
   Recommendations for researchers include the development of standardized
   guidelines for AI tool usage in academic settings. The impact on society
   involves enhancing digital literacy and ethical standards among future
   professionals. Future research should explore the long-term effects of
   AI integration in education and its implications for academic integrity.},
