Note = {27th International Conference on Interactive Collaborative Learning-ICL,
   Tallinn, ESTONIA, SEP 24-27, 2024},
Abstract = {This study investigates the effects of a novel systematic approach to
   student-partner assignment for collaborative learning sessions in
   university Computer Science courses. The method utilizes assessments,
   specifically quizzes, administered in pairs, or dyads. Students complete
   the first quiz in a dyad independently and the second collaboratively
   with a partner. A student's results from the first quiz determine their
   partner for the second, ensuring some degree of variability in the
   understanding of course concepts between the two students. The method is
   tested in multiple sections of two distinct university courses to
   explore whether student learning is influenced by the knowledge level of
   their partner, and whether the cumulative effect of partner assignments
   impacts a student's overall performance in the course. One of the
   courses comprises first and second-year university students while the
   other is composed of third or fourth-year students. Statistical
   analyses, which utilize quiz-question embeddings generated by a large
   language model, proved inconclusive on the relationship between
   concept-specific knowledge and student learning. However, results
   indicate a positive correlation such that students who have partners
   with varying knowledge levels (relative to their own) performed better
   in the course overall. This relationship was statistically significant
   in courses for first and second-year students suggesting that deliberate
   partner assignment for collaborative learning may benefit students at
   the beginning of their university journey more than those further on in
   their academic journey.},
